   "source": [
    "# Time Dependent Quantum Mechanics\n",
    "\n",
    "The week before we have started to analyze stationary quantum mechanical problems with the help of the stationary Schrödinger equation. \n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "-i\\hbar\\frac{\\partial \\Psi}{\\partial t}=-\\frac{\\hbar^2}{2m}\\nabla^2 \\Psi + V(x)\\Psi\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "This time we will have a look at the time dependent Schrödinger equation, which allows us to look at the dynamics of the wavefunction in a system. Before we do that, we wish to explore wavepackets, which are constructed by superpositions of plane wave solutions. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Wave Packets"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The following plots show the composition of wavepackets as a superposition of multiple waves with different k-vectors. It also compares the wavepacket propagation for matter waves and light waves.\n",
    "\n",
    "A wavepacket can be constructed from a superposition of plane waves with different wavenumber $k$ or different frequency $\\omega$. We write down examples only for the wavenumber, but equivalently, they may be developed for the frequency as well. \n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\\psi(x)=A\\int\\limits_{+\\infty}^{-\\infty}\\phi(k)e^{ikx}e^{-i\\omega t}dk\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "The function $\\phi(k)$ gives the amplitude of the wavefunction with the value $k$ in the wavepacket. If for example only one wave at $k_0$ is contributing to the wavepacket, then the function $\\phi(k_0)=1$ but for all other $k$ this function is zero. Therefore the integral results only in a single plane wave.\n",
    "\n",
    "If the distribution of amplitudes $\\phi(k)$ extends over a larger region, i.e. from $k_{0}-\\Delta k/2$ to $k_{0}+\\Delta k/2$, the wavepacket is more complex. For matter waves we have to take into account that $\\omega$ is a function of the wavevector as well.\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\\omega=\\frac{\\hbar k^{2}}{2m}\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "To calculate the shape of the wavepacket we approximate the above dispersion relation by\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\\omega=\\omega_0+\\frac{\\partial \\omega}{\\partial k}(k-k_{0})\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "which replaces the above dispersion relation by an approximate linear one. \n",
    "\n",
    "As a final result we obtain the wavepacket \n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\\psi(x,t)=2A\\frac{\\sin\\left(x-\\frac{\\partial \\omega}{\\partial k}t\\right)\\frac{\\Delta k}{2}}{x-\\frac{\\partial \\omega}{\\partial k}t}e^{i(k_0x-\\omega_0 t)}\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "Obviously the wavepacket has an underlying plane wave which is the rightmost exponential factor. The fator in front of the plane wave defines the envelope of the wavepacket. The envelope appears through the superposition of all plane waves. It propagates with the group velocity $v_{g}=\\partial \\omega/\\partial k$, while the plane wave propagates with the phase velocity $v_{ph}=\\omega_{0}/k_0$, which can be different than the group velocity. \n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "The superposition of such plane waves resulting in wave packets as demonstrated with the functions \n",
    "\n",
    "~~~\n",
    "def matter_wave_packet(x,t):\n",
    "\n",
    "def gauss_wave_packet(x,t):\n",
    "\n",
    "~~~\n",
    "\n",
    "**matter_wave_packet** reveals a wave packet for electrons at a wavelength of 1 Angstrom and a finite with constant amplitude distribution for the plane waves.\n",
    "\n",
    "**gauss_wave_packet** reveals a matter wave packet for electrons at a wavelength of 1 Angstrom and a gaussian amplitude distribution for the plane waves. \n"
   ]

    "## Definition of the wave packet functions\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 112,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": true,
    "jupyter": {
     "outputs_hidden": true
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# matter wave packet with a frequency that scales with the square of the wave vector\n",
    "def matter_wave_packet(x,t):\n",
    "    h=0\n",
    "    N=100\n",
    "    for k in np.linspace(k0-dk,k0+dk,N):\n",
    "        frequency=hbar*k**2/(2*electron_mass)\n",
    "        h+=np.exp(1j*(k*x-frequency*t))/N        \n",
    "                \n",
    "    return(h)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def gauss_wave_packet(x,t):\n",
    "    h=0\n",
    "    for k in np.linspace(k0-dk,k0+dk,1000):\n",
    "        frequency=hbar*k**2/(2*electron_mass)\n",
    "        sigma=np.sqrt(2)*0.2*dk\n",
    "        h+=np.exp(-((k-k0)/sigma)**2)*np.exp(1j*(k*x-frequency*t))        \n",
    "    return(h)\n"
   ]

   "source": [
    "## Time Evolution of a Wavepacket in a Potential Box\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "![Particle_In_Box.png](Particle_In_Box.png)\n",
    "\n",
    "While so far we have looked at the wave packet in free space, we want to confine the object now by a potential and watch the time evolution of this wave packet in the potential.\n",
    "The time dependent Schrödinger equation is given by\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "-i\\hbar\\frac{\\partial \\Psi}{\\partial t}=-\\frac{\\hbar^2}{2m}\\nabla^2 \\Psi + V(x)\\Psi\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "For a potential box with infinite walls and width $d$, the potential energy in the box can be set to zero. The Schrödinger equation within the box therefore reduces to\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\\label{eq:se}\n",
    "-i\\hbar\\frac{\\partial \\Psi}{\\partial t}=-\\frac{\\hbar^2}{2m}\\nabla^2 \\Psi \n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "This differential equation in dimension can be solved using a Fourier series expansion of the wave function $\\Psi$.\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\\label{eq:psi}\n",
    "\\Psi(x,t)=\\sum_{n=1}^\\infty C_n(t) \\sin\\left(\\frac{n\\pi}{d}x\\right)\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "The $sine$ function represents the corresponding boundary conditions, i.e. that $\\Psi(x=0)=0$ and $\\Psi(x=d)=0$. The time dependence of the wave function is encoded in the prefactors $C_n(t)$. Inserting  eq. \\ref{eq:psi} into the Schrödinger equation \\ref{eq:se} yields\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "i\\sum_{n=1}^\\infty \\dot{C}_n(t) \\sin\\left(\\frac{n\\pi}{d}x\\right)=\\frac{\\hbar^2}{2m}\\sum_{n=1}^\\infty C_n(t) \\frac{n^2\\pi^2}{d^2}\\sin\\left(\\frac{n\\pi}{d}x\\right)\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "To obtain a differential equation for the coefficient $C_n(t)$ we multiply both sides of the latter equation with $\\sin\\left(\\frac{l\\pi}{d}x\\right)$ and integrate from $0$ to $d$. Doing this on the left side yields\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "i\\int_{0}^{d} \\sum_{n=1}^\\infty \\dot{C}_n(t) \\sin\\left(\\frac{n\\pi}{d}x\\right)\\sin\\left(\\frac{l\\pi}{d}x\\right)dx\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "An equvalent operation can be carried out on the right side. The orthogonality of the $sine$-basis yields for $n=l$\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\\label{eq:deq}\n",
    "\\dot{C}_n(t)=-i\\frac{\\hbar k^2}{2m}C_n(t)\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "which can be solved with the ansatz\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "C_n(t)=C_{0n} e^{\\lambda t}\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "Inserting this ansatz into eq. \\ref{eq:deq} yields\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\\lambda=-i\\frac{\\hbar k^2}{2m}=-i\\omega\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "with $k^2=\\frac{n^2\\pi^2}{d^2}$. Thus the final solution of the time dependent Schrödinger equation for a wave paket in a box potential reads\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\\Psi(x,t)=\\sum_{n=1}^\\infty C_{0n}\\, e^{-i\\frac{\\hbar n^2\\pi^2}{2m d^2}t} \\sin\\left(\\frac{n\\pi}{d}x\\right)\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "The coefficients $C_{0n}$ follow from the initial conditions $\\Psi(x,t=0)=\\Psi(x)$. \n",
    "\n",
    "### Initial Conditions and more Details \n",
    "\n",
    "For this project $\\Psi(x)$ shall be assumed to be a Gaussian wave packet centered around different positions in the box. Also other initial conditions such as triangular shaped wavepackets may be considered. Different states of the temporal evolution of the probability density of the wave packet shall be plotted and saved together with an animation of its time evolution. \n",
    "\n",
    "The students shall study the time evolution of the wave packet for different masses and spatial extents. \n",
    "\n",
    "As an additional task, the students shall address the superposition of the different Eigenstates of the box."
   ]

    "def wave(x): # initial wave\n",
    "    return(np.exp(-(x-1)**2/0.05))\n",
    "\n",
    "def f(x,n,d):\n",
    "    return(np.sin(n*np.pi*x/d))\n",
    "    \n",
    "def integrate(fun,n,d,a,b):\n",
    "    x=np.arange(a,b,np.abs(a-b)/10000)\n",
    "    fu=fun(x)*f(x,n,d)\n",
    "    return(np.sum(fu)*np.abs(a-b)/10000)\n",
    "\n",
    "def init(x,num):\n",
    "    c0n=np.zeros(num)\n",
    "    for n in range(len(c0n)):\n",
    "        c0n[n]=integrate(wave,n,np.pi,0,np.pi)\n",
    "    return(c0n)\n",
    "\n",
    "def w_func(x,d,c0n,t):\n",
    "    psi=0\n",
    "    for n in range(len(c0n)):\n",
    "        psi=psi+c0n[n]*np.exp(-complex(0,n**2*np.pi**2*t/(2*m*d**2)))*f(x,n,d)\n",
    "    return(psi)   \n",
    "\n",
    "def g(xp):\n",
    "    s=0\n",
    "    for l in range(len(c0n)):\n",
    "       s=s+c0n[l]*f(xp,l,np.pi)\n",
    "    return(s)"
   ]

    "\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from matplotlib import animation\n",
    "\n",
    "%matplotlib \n",
    "#%config InlineBackend.figure_format = 'retina'\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "fig = plt.figure(1,figsize=(5,5))\n",
    "ax = plt.axes(xlim=(0, np.pi), ylim=(0,0.02))\n",
    "line, = ax.plot([],[],lw=2)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# initialization function: plot the background of each frame\n",
    "def init1():\n",
    "    line.set_data([], [])\n",
    "    #ax.add_patch(patch)\n",
    "    return line,\n",
    "\n",
    "# animation function.  This is called sequentially\n",
    "def animate(i):\n",
    "    lpx=xp\n",
    "    lpy=np.abs(w_func(xp,np.pi,c0n,i/10.0))**2\n",
    "    s=sum(lpy)\n",
    "    line.set_data(lpx,lpy/s)\n",
    "    return line,\n",
    "\n",
    "anim = animation.FuncAnimation(fig, animate, init_func=init1,\n",
    "                               frames=2000, interval=50, blit=False)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()\n",
    "\n"
   ]
